Yes — that is the right move. Build a new internal base image once, push it as its own project, then make pxe-content use that as DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE.

The important thing: do not keep installing Python inside the pxe-content image. Put Python in the new base image.

1. Set your image names

Adjust the new image path if your GitLab project path is slightly different.

BASE_IMAGE="registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/images/base-images/nginx-alpine:latest"
NEW_IMAGE="registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/images/nginx-python-alpine:latest"

Pull and inspect the current image:

podman login registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com
podman pull "$BASE_IMAGE"
podman run --rm "$BASE_IMAGE" sh -lc '
cat /etc/os-release || true
nginx -v || true
command -v apk || true
python3 --version || true
'

You should see nginx, apk, and probably no python3.

2. Create the new nginx-python-alpine project files

Create a new folder locally:

mkdir -p nginx-python-alpine
cd nginx-python-alpine

Create Dockerfile:

ARG DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE
FROM ${DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE}
USER 0
RUN if ! command -v apk >/dev/null 2>&1; then \
      echo "ERROR: this image is expected to be Alpine-based and have apk." >&2; \
      exit 1; \
    fi
RUN apk add --no-cache python3
RUN nginx -v && python3 --version

That is all this image needs for your current PXE generator. No pip is needed because your Python script uses standard library modules only.

3. Build it locally

podman build \
  --pull=never \
  --build-arg DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE="$BASE_IMAGE" \
  -t "$NEW_IMAGE" \
  .

Test it:

podman run --rm "$NEW_IMAGE" sh -lc '
nginx -v
python3 --version
command -v python3
'

4. Push it to the new GitLab project registry

podman push "$NEW_IMAGE"

Optional but recommended: also push a dated tag so you are not only relying on latest.

DATE_TAG="$(date +%Y%m%d)"
DATED_IMAGE="${NEW_IMAGE%:latest}:${DATE_TAG}"
podman tag "$NEW_IMAGE" "$DATED_IMAGE"
podman push "$DATED_IMAGE"

5. Update pxe-content/.gitlab-ci.yml

Change this:

DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE: "registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/images/base-images/nginx-alpine:latest"

To this:

DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE: "registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/images/nginx-python-alpine:latest"

Or use the dated tag for repeatability:

DOCKER_FROM_IMAGE: "registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/images/nginx-python-alpine:20260503"

6. Keep the simplified pxe-content Dockerfile

Once the new base image has Python, your pxe-content Dockerfile should not run apk add python3 anymore.

Keep this kind of check only:

RUN command -v python3 >/dev/null 2>&1 || \
    (echo "ERROR: base image must include python3." >&2 && exit 1)

Important warning

The new nginx-python-alpine project pipeline may fail the same way if GitLab CI still cannot reach the Alpine package repo. Your local build and push will solve the immediate issue because the final image already contains Python.

Later, for a fully repeatable CI build, the nginx-python-alpine project needs one of these:

1. access to an internal Alpine package mirror, or
2. an internal base image that already includes python3, or
3. a vendored/offline apk package approach

For now, local build → push internal image → use it in pxe-content is a good practical path.